odges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Adele Luzarches married Amaury II de Meulan, Sgr de Meulan et de la Queue-en-Brie before 1231. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","1194–1252":"1194–1252","1225–1252":"1225–1252","1230–1274":"1230–1274","–1260":"–1260","–Female":"Surnud","1225":"1225","before 1231":"enne 1231","about 1225":"umbes 1225","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1252":"1252","1260":"1260","1194":"1194","about 1230":"umbes 1230","Meulan-en-Yvelines, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France":"Meulan-en-Yvelines, Yvelines, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","1194–1252":"1194–1252","1225–1252":"1225–1252","1230–1274":"1230–1274","–1260":"–1260","–Female":"Kuollut","1225":"1225","before 1231":"ennen vuotta 1231","about 1225":"noin 1225","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1252":"1252","1260":"1260","1194":"1194","about 1230":"noin 1230","Meulan-en-Yvelines, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France":"Meulan-en-Yvelines, Yvelines, Île-de-France, Ranska","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"–":"Décédée","1194–1252":"1194–1252","1225–1252":"1225–1252","1230–1274":"1230–1274","–1260":"–1260","–Female":"Décédée","1225":"1225","before 1231":"avant 1231","about 1225":"environ 1225","1274":"1274","1230":"1230","1252":"1252","1260":"1260","1194":"1194","about 1230":"environ 1230","Meulan-en-Yvelines, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France":"Meulan-en-Yvelines, Yvelines, Île-de-France, France","France":"France","lifeSummary":"Adele Luzarches a épousé Amaury II de Meulan, Sgr de Meulan et de la Queue-en-Brie avant 1231. Ils ont eu au moins 3 fils."},"de":{"–":"Verstorben","1194–1252":"1194–1252","1225–1252":"1225–1252","1230–1274":"1230–1274","–1260":"–1260","–Female":"Verstorben","1225":"1225","before 1231":"vor 1231","about 1225":"um 1225","1274":"1274","1230":"123